At the end of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange bascula in the negative
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the start of the exchanges, the Prague stock market resumed with its fall the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market's reaction to the result of the US House of Representatives' vote, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilization plan, is thus also noticeable here.
Fall of stocks in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, although the indices managed to erase some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trades, but later wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Chinese stock movement on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“The hesitancy about rescue action in the US will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should soon resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The Bloodbath of American Actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly 12 billion K<0xC4><0x8D>).
Lawmakers thus rejected the call for support of President George Bush’s bill.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday and the main stock indices saw the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a drop of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress cedes: U.S. government may inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the U.S. financial aid agreement.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turn in talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of a $700 billion financial aid (about 12 trillion crowns) granted to the U.S. financial system.
The success is not so sure.
Indeed, before Congress can publish the final version of the law and submit it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, Barney Frank, the chairman of the House’s banking and financial regulation committee, told Reuters.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be adopted should be a major psychological factor to revive financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, there will be a "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the shape the package of measures should have for market stabilization,” Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
She said the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, to give the bottom of the government a final shape.
It should buy out, from financial companies, the unsoldable real estate assets that cause financial companies significant losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the stock markets that are falling.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are making sure that Congress comes to a definitive agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect Monday’s trade.
But for the moment, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will vote, or whether the negotiations will not be blocked at the last minute by one or another problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still be subject to many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wished, must be made available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the granting of the remaining amount by following two steps: first $100 billion extra, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed progress in the negotiations.
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress, he has the opportunity to put it in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted of obtaining funding for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed on Sunday to vote on the bill, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President George W. Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated “the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of Golden Parachute
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said the legislators agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of taxpayers against losses, the settlement agreement, and the timeline plan.
The new law also provides for limiting the said gold parachute for directors of the companies participating in the program and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides for aid for property owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new deposits in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is because we don't know what the mechanism and the price of the purchase of problematic assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the share of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is not as important as that, according to Marek.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree, as of this week, that they support this plan and that they will consecrate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, foreseeing the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek said.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
It does not prevent that there are sufficient reasons to acquire an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album by Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you’re at least probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music on the move, that is, of compressed music, to put it simply - of music in MP3.
There, too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time bearing headphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
There are two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the first functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to read music and movies, to record the latter, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you’ll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no TV will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal nature of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the lower the interval between two recharges.
And playing music is one of the most important energy buckets.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are significantly more performant.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect them to play music only for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is true even for more expensive devices.
There will be no problem for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of a recharge, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording the music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
One can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card players know how to do it without a reduction, given the small dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As for the drives, you don’t need, except for the iPod, any software.
Just fill up, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers will create their own media library, sorted by the performer's name, album title, style, or by the user's judgment.
Some devices display only one index with a tree structure, in the way of Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In the choice of a concrete device, you are especially interested in the life of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of output of the sound and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile playing the MP3s.
Virtually all mobile phones are capable of doing so today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player is able to play.
Everyone gets to read the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will get to you will have just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also get to play music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you need to do is visit the corresponding operator (or another provider) web pages from your mobile phone and purchase the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to purchase a music mobile.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is, in most cases, limited to radio tubes made quickly.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, the Internet, or even the wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their phones on themselves.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the phone out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones on you or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobile phones, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three thousand crowns, one can already have a very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for regular headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also provided with an entry for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Indeed, anyone who manages to control the most rudimentary drives - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command to that of a cassette record, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have an interchangeable memory card slot (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get away with even 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, buy a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iris.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and so the ease of the control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the most far in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Might be.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz many times that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the area of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of the Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no more room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network apparently no longer has much luck (by the way, now he would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the conventional operators were subsequently to respond as well.
Yet, even before the entry of party-disturbances such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those that are heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We don’t have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
In addition, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among other things.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they do indeed need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
Now, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good ad.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
“The real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our home as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project to success, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promotional.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
Instead, they try to do their best to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not been hiding, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner will be the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not consider that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific in comparison with others.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet recorded a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate within such a limited time frame, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to fulfilling requests for its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most contributions from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
What good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to understand each other as larrons at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when creating the U:fon, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the web pages of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
Now, today, the U:phone is ready to serve as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> remarked: “Competition in the mobile market has recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators as follows, the indifference of the Czech regulators seems confusing.
However, this is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, because the offer of potential stakeholders a priori has not shown sufficient interest for the classical operators," said Kristian Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
A statement made in this way would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
Especially since Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile phone services."
However, putting pressure on the fair functioning of the market and the price drop does not appear to be in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concordance of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
“The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their market behaviour.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator,” Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator logically enough has the monopoly on its network.
This is why it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they are facing similar constraints in the negotiations with all operators.
Putting the responsibility back on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common thread in communications, through which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted telecoms law has failed to bring about an extension of the powers of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one is watching, it can work.
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a matter of companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic round is that the business done in front of the operator is a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are talking about happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and that could result in a termination of cooperation with the company in question," said Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the managers of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, and at the same time, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question is posed to <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a significant drop in the price of services.
However, in virtually every country where virtual operators appeared, the classical operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulators intervened in developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the same way as a hot potato that is disposed of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the cuff after the knee.
If behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will be unable to remain impassioned in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Day of Czech Nationality, Prime Minister Mirek Topol<0xC3><0xA1>nek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is insured by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD>nkov<0xC3><0xA1> and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremia<0xC5><0xA1> and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek are the authors of the anthem arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek considers the Czech national anthem as one of the most beautiful anthems.
As he had previously entrusted to <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> rözhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to make sure that both singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that we could understand the lyrics, that they were singing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j resounds for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of the States) in Fidlova<0xC4><0x8D>ka (Kermesse des salvetiers), original Czech play by Josef Kajet<0xC3><0xA1>n Tyl, accompanied by music by Franti<0xC5><0xA1>ek <0xC5><0xA0>kroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
