I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, one can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hardly practicable terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least, therefore, for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might reside in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, is neither measured nor analyzed by this particular Hardware, based on our own experience, then its observation poses major problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious experience, but there is next to it another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their content, and this is exactly what happened when studying the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also underlines the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does it mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its aftermath, such as the reactions of the body) captures living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute them to others other than ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the body sensation regions of the cortex and the brain stem, just like Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could be quite involved in transversal sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in humans and rats is likely to be felt as such in both cases: how, however, could one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees in the face of danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Of course, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain stems, while cockroaches don’t even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the cause of the sensations?
And even if we could prove it for humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations probably differ completely from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is on the nerve plane insofar as the same is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I do not know if they exist.
We could think of this as short-term, but I'd rather move forward than knock myself constantly against a wall.
I am indeed a pragmatic emotionalist.
