The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, bigger every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not on typical images.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you do not need to take photos on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars.”
With the festival "Popular Mining Song", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and hardware, recall the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the singing itself, but about the personality and character of the artist that captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essentials and the magic has been the constant of this work that we present these days in the gallery El Fotomata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book collection of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph people's portraits, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment more or less.
I believe that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don’t know or that leave you only a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I’m still trying to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the Galerie El Fotomata, located at 20 rue de la Mata (street parallel to the People's Square of Hercules), which will be open until 16 October.
