Its aim is to reintegrate the driver by offering him/her road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety as well as the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers stopped for driving more than once in a drunken state, resume the car.
The alcohol lock would avoid this since it is a connected system on the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than the one allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the expense of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain, it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people each year.
This measure only applies to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, nevertheless, reform done by criminal means requires reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one for experimental purposes.
