Talking while sleeping
Some children talk at night.
I’m not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk while they sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called sleepiness.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime numbness (pissing in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful or over-excited situations.
This is an unstudied phenomenon, anyway.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a small quiet voice, with isolated words, whispers, or vice versa with screams, tears, long speeches...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another alteration of sleep that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to bed.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the somniloquies appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because it's unconscious and you'd wake it up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or to check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he’s saying (which is not usual), don’t be tempted to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because in sleep he is not conscious in order to be able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
