The Interview - Blood Resurrected
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the most safe and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public’s confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the grimness of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from recurring.
While Judge Krever was late to file his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was disheartening.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field over the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
From its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, Europe was witnessing the outbreak of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, according to which when it is not known and that a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death.
In April 1999, the blood of persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was therefore refused.
However, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs) that make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have shortened the mute period, which spans between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors become infected without knowing it and that they cannot be detected.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product to occur.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continued before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
“Requirements are increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets to be recharged.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average only includes 3% of Quebecers who are eligible for blood donation."
However, any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is severe, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Today’s life is so stressful, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago the bankrolling of our thousandth sample of cord blood, and it is expected to take more than a thousand samples per year.
We should start proposing for transplants at the beginning of next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," as Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
