Free Opinion - Le discourse orwellien de Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
Prosecuting an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small undisclosed publishing house with the aim of launching a “transparent public debate”.
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of prosecutions in defamation, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a friendly settlement that will blush the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to look back on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada usually take place through the exchange of ideas and not through the exchange of ideas.
So it was enough for the mine to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust the public and rejects petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada from the back of the hand.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public debate" at the same time while disrespecting the opinions of that same public?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers only to fat-paid lawyers and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because he rejects the brutal manner of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a whistle-blower (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has, moreover, filed a statement of intent in place of Black Canada's authors.
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s prosecution is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in block, the right to citation of credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that dislike the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under repetition, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the academic world, as well as to the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place arrangements to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It includes: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of committed public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative to the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done in such a way as to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“That’s the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, the chaos and the disruptions on Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” Republican Judd Gregg said.
Negotiations had turned to the sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that would cause a new failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline we agreed on was the opening of the markets this morning.
Late in the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has been credited with adding some provisions to the deal, including the one to allow owners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of business leaders rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on the US television broadcasts.
Asked about another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, Republican opponent John McCain responded, “I’d like to see the details, but I hope so.”
“The big lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back dubious, risky, and unsold claims from U.S. financial institutions with taxpayers’ money.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the collapse of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of financing and banning credit securities (PCAA) and institutions on a freeze-out.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had led the first draft of the deal last week.
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since the Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the corner for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it regain its placement.
The new plan envisages the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion, to which another $100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion is expected to be approved by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescue companies that will be worth dividends in case of profits and that it will be able to resell when the turmoil passes.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the seizure procedures for housing attached to the real estate loans affected by this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and starting allowances paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
In fact, votes continued to rise against this project yesterday, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
It’s not about benefiting taxpayers.”
Animator of a small group in Congress dubbed the "Caucus of Skeptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had given up on acquiring its insolvent competitor since it lost <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion to the U.S. in the loan crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, we regain a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It’s exactly something that savers and households appreciate now that the times are getting uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank plagued by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take back all of the loans underway at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government is expected to nationalize since the start of this financial crisis.
