The psychology of over-the-counter: why do we spend more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a play auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants were able to earn money, but during the auction of which an essential element is the over-auction of a third, the ensemble under the brain stem, called the striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the escape from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, economists from this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups oversold in front of a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and so they carried out their placement.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received the $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on victory in one group, while in the other group, on failure.
Proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
