Hepatitis: When Should I See a Doctor?
Around the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that patients with the hepatitis virus are 100 miles away in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment, which is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and the diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g.: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through the blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travelers are advised to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to get the virus, because the pathogenic gene sourly destroys the cells of the liver. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating doctor as soon as the observation of symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of a cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick from around the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
