The smart car mimics the flight of the bourdon
What method would be better to develop technologies that are capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, the bees.
In the astonishing project presented at CEATEC, which takes place in Japan, buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of starting, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a robotic mini car, a bio-inspired self-roboted control system, type BR23C, that it has equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval-shaped, which in reality looks a lot like our safe protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department.
The bee's facetted eye plays a primary role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the facet eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If this were not the case, the mini auto robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where at the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotational movement, acceleration and slowing as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is larger, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don’t need memory with a capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology that serves instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entrance into mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles in its path.
