The super glue to walk on the walls.
Overcome the laws of gravity through super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100 kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
ETUDE- The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called nanocarbon tubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a spaghetti pile," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that allow to ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "easily detachs itself from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at Day's faculty.
“This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
May be to walk on walls like Spiderman? May be yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electrical current.
Other applications could be related to aerospace engineering.
At the moment, no superhero.
OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibers like hair, which self-cleanses dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medications: never with fruit juices.
Pay attention to grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed mainly in the summer because they are dehydrating and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital drugs, alter their amplifying or decreasing absorption, as the case may be, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether they are, in cans or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th National Health Meeting of the American Chemical Society's staff at the American Chemical Society.
Grapefruit juice has already been strongly criticized for being held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stimulated and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
MEDICINES AT RISK- It is the Italian Agency of the drug itself, which had given the news in a two-year newsletter, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mixture and to pay attention to what you drink, if you take the Mémzé or Diapa, for example.
According to experts, even orange juice and apple juice contain substances that inhibit the use of medications.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are generally immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies that will need to change the informational notes of the medicines.
It is always necessary to read the illustrative papers of the drugs you take, and, if something is not clear, do not be impressed, but address clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," the expert told the agency Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the localization of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a New-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a famous New York Times editor.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy solutions.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman wrote, in an article published in the New York Times, that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on U.S. history.
A prediction that sparked many controversy, and which was blamed on the economist for years, but which now turned out to be accurate.
“I am surprised and even a little shocked at how quickly the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public’s attention,” Krugman said.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a "high-value economist", but also a very aggressive "disseminator", particularly critical of the Bush administration's excesses of liberalism.
Open Office, the third edition of the “anti-Microsoft” package
It is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
Following almost a year of work done by volunteer developers, supervised by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is shown to the general public with various novelties: from the welcome screen, and the ISO-reviewed interface and became less austere, to the latest standard, to newer, newer, formatted version.
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open the documents with the new extension of Microsoft (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting, some features specific to certain modules, such as the one that allows to reduce the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, for sending them by e-mail, or for importing PDF files into the graphic design module, retaining the original appearance of the page.
On this front, it is always possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical Adobe-format graphics with the elements of a spreadsheet or text developer.
Multi-person collaboration is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts on modifications, in the drafting of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a color of comments for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some OpenOffice features to the web (on the cloud, on the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they are expected to issue the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and is added to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be shipped at home or at the workplace.
And if the theme of free will can be a way to spread it in the homes, it is precisely in the business, that Open Office subsequently tries the big challenge, which can already count on various projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer a training, consultation and support service, ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which could also open up to business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the equivalent writing video of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for rival PowerPoint presentations; Dbase, such as the famous Access, is the program that allows you to work on the databases; finally Drwa is the graph module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today there are almost 3 million and 600 miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, one can even exceed the expected figure
