Students who are victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest survey of the Sunia, the tenant union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of exclusion of entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high global costs that families from which they come must support," explains the head of the department of studies in the Sunia department, Laura Mariani, who was responsible for the development of these cities.
In most cases, the rental offers also involve a series of violations: free-type contracts, unregistered, no rental limit, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the taxation are needed to calm the prices.
Looking at the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in Brianza zone, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from a minimum of 650 euros (zone Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (zone Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (zone Vitttoria)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Values slightly lower (550 euros for a single) for areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
One can only save if one moves away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 euros for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or the like.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, it is spent from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei zones.
In Bari, for a bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra-community students, register a further anomaly: the rent requested from foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities feed the historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favor of multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of the marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, it is often historical places and charged with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of the way and so many emotions" observes the one that the director of the Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, and the first film of the film, which he offers to Tornatore 20.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional-type cinemas have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have mostly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Palermo and Tur, 6 less in Rome.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is at the top with 82 cinemas mono rooms lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 additional screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a farm in a city, these frequencies are not necessarily all willing to go multiplex to.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of the credit in favour of merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono-room cinemas in the historical centers and in the outskirts.
The regulations envisaged include measures of tax facilitation for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
