When the energy comes from the waves, now the big ones launch.
This is an excessive deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which giants like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now they are trying to get their hands on it.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has now been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now ecologists and the new rise in oil are giving a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore systems.
This amount would be twice that of nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides..
Colossians attacking.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in the north of Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, one would have said a real revolutionary step.
Two years after that, more and more candidates among these companies have always been dedicated to traditional energy bet on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying technologies on ocean energy,” said a spokesperson for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant, the Wall Street Journal, and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if we consider that precisely in Alaska, the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for further excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are New York’s Greenland Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power, which traverse the path of energy coming from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, according to the observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology even in its early days, apart from the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create a major problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher ecological impact.
And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure causes a turbine to rotate, which in turn, feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through underwater cables.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Greening Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines on the East River in New York.
The movement of water during tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the permits needed to extract energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, deserves at this time, the potential of the tides.
Although this is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable by wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coasts, invested $7.5 million in 2008, and anticipates investments up to $35 million in 2009.
